name: Lev Shuster

paradigm.text:
----Online Tournaments---
---At The Start of the Round---
Before the round begins, please unmute yourself for a quick mic check (tell us what you had for breakfast)
I encourage small talk between competitors before and after the round.
---In Round--
Please time yourself and opponents, if a opponent goes substantially over time you are welcome to unmute to remind them.
When feasible, please keep your cameras on even when not speaking, though having one's webcam off is completely understandable when necessary.
I work off two displays so if I'm looking off camera don't despair :)
----Classic Debate----
While I never debated in Classic , I did debate in World Schools, Public Forum, and Big Question Debate in high school which all share some similarities with Classic Debate.
I vote off my notes and try to minimize judge intervention.
Because I was raised in other debate types, my Jargon may be confusing. Please let me know what feedback doesn't make sense!
I'm still calibrating to classics debate judging, thus my main paradigm in not applicable to classics debate. Below are a blippy list of expectations that apply to Classics Debate.
I despise power tagging so please accurately represent your evidence.
I'm good with any Classics Debate talking speed.
Organization and efficiency in rebuttals will increase your speaker points dramatically.
Each team should present a consistent narrative between speakers.
I do not care if you sit or stand during any speech or cross-examination.
see -Background- and -Contact Info- below for additional pertinent information
----All Other Formats----
---Overview---
No matter the debate format (including Public Forum and World School Debate) I am a flow judge: I will take close notes of the content for each speech and vote based on my notes.
If at any point I cannot follow your speech, I will proclaim “clear” as warning. There will be no Speaker Point deduction associated with the first warning.
Debaters are expected to keep time and each other accountable.
Whatever you argue, I will evaluate, full stop. Below are my preferences and slight biases, not rules/expectations.
---Contact Info---
Lev Shuster (He/Him/His)
Email: "shusterl" concatenated with "@carleton" and then ".edu"
---Background---
Three years of high school Policy Debate out of Washington state.
One year of high school Lincoln Douglas Debate.
Additional success in World Schools and Big Question Debate.
Competed in Public Forum and Parliamentary debate.
Currently a student at Carleton College.
---Ballots and Speaker points---
When deciding a winner, delivery has very little weight. Delivery is only a factor (along with strategy) when assigning speaker points.
To combat Speaker Point bias, I will strive to provide written rationalization for speaker ranks.
Unless specifically banned by the tournament, I’m happy to disclose when asked by participants.
---Problematic Argumentation---
Provide trigger warnings if appropriate to your opponent before the round begins.
If I say something problematic and you feel comfortable saying something, call me out and you may earn an additional Speaker Points.
Overtly problematic argumentation is one of the few times I will intervene with actions including, but not limited to, tanking Speaker Points.
It is never the burden of competitors to call out problematic argumentation. However, if competitors feel comfortable bringing up such acts as an independent voting issues I consistently find such argumentation persuasive.
Recognize that everyone makes mistakes and that we should all strive to help the debate community grow.
---Notes for more progressive debate environments: General---
I have a high threshold for theory from the negation. I'm fine voting on potential abuse. Theory needs substantial voters and analysis work done for me to consider voting on it.
If you’re running a performance case I would rather you keep up the performance throughout the round, and have a way for the other team to compete/participate in the performance.
I don’t mind experimental or “Meme” rounds when the other team has some way to participate.
In K or theory driven rounds, I particularly appreciate being told the point of the ballot.
---Notes for more progressive debate environments: Speed---
Three years of Policy Debate has given me a tolerance for speed. However, unclear spreading is a common cause of speaker-point deduction. I haven’t done high speed debate recently so, particularly for Policy debate, slow down on your tags and pull out warrants in later speeches.
When choosing to spread, be mindful of your opponent’s exposure to high speed debate. I do expect you to provide opponents some form of written case (printed copy, email, flash drive, or passing over your computer during cross-examination) if they request it.
---Notes for more progressive debate environments: Critiques---
Do not assume I know the literature.
The link needs to be strong, specific, and very clearly linked to case. Unmoored or vague links make me grumpy.
For non mainstream K’s, please provide me with a overview/underview that explains what the K is trying to accomplish.
When I was a debater, I found the most helpful question when considering running a K was if my judge was formerly a K debater. My answer has a twist: my peak of critical exploration was an uninterrupted year in which I only ran a niche Biopower K; the following year I did not run a single K. Take that as you will...
---Additional Notes---
I do not flow cross-examination.
Clearly signpost and label arguments by topic not just by author.
I believe every formats point is to persuade. I recognize the different form of persuasion from traditional persuasive speaking to explicit Value/Criterion evaluation. I will judge and appreciate whatever you preferred balance of persuasion may be.
If an entirely new argument is brought up after constructive speeches, I will not evaluate it.
I will default to an utilitarian calculus if nothing else is provided.
I do not care if you sit or stand during any speech or cross-examination.
Tag-teaming and off-time road-maps are fine when reasonably practiced.
If there is an email-chain already started you’re welcome to include me. However, I will never read your case while the round is in progress. If I miss a line, too bad. I will only open a document or request to see a case if an argument about the specific wording of a document is carried through to the round’s conclusion.
If your arguments don’t have a seed of truth and you aren’t called out great, I will not intervene.
I appreciate those who can make me laugh with off the cuff remarks.
My priorities are for competitors to learn, be considerate, and have fun!
---Things that make me particularly happy---
I really like case debate, extend the case, and outweigh with the case.
Each team should present a consistent narrative between speakers.
Collapse into one clear story by your last speech.
Explicitly compare your impacts to your opponent's (timeframe, probability, and magnitude).
Organization and efficiency in rebuttals will increase your speaker points dramatically.

	<script type="text/javascript">

        $(document).ready(function() {

			$("#judgerecord").tablesorter({
				cssAsc           : "sortup",
				cssDesc          : "sortdown",
				cssHeader        : "sortable",
				sortInitialOrder : "desc",
				saveFileName 	 : "judgerecord.csv",
				widgets     : ['zebra', 'columns', 'stickyHeaders', 'print', 'output'],
				initialized : function(table) {
					// Tablesorter disrupts the focus auto feature inside itself.  This works around.
					$(".focushere").focus();
				},
				widgetOptions : {
					columns          : [ "primary", "secondary", "tertiary" ],
					print_rows       : "f",
					print_columns    : "v",
					print_now        : true,
					print_styleSheet : "/lib/css/print.css",
					output_saveRows  : "visible",
					output_delivery  : "download",
				}
			});



				var printButtonHTML = "<button id='print_judgerecord' tabindex='-1' class='notfirst printbutton buttonwhite redtext fa fa-sm fa-print marleft'>";

				var outputButtonHTML = "<button id='output_judgerecord' tabindex='-1' class='notfirst printbutton buttonwhite greentext fa fa-sm fa-file-excel-o marleft'>";

				if ( $("#judgerecord_buttonarea").length) {

						$("#judgerecord_buttonarea").append(printButtonHTML);

					$("#judgerecord_buttonarea").append(outputButtonHTML);

				} else {

					var beginButtonRow = "<span id='judgerecord_buttonarea' class='nospace half rightalign right'>";
					var endButtonRow = "";

					$("#judgerecord")
						.before(beginButtonRow+outputButtonHTML+printButtonHTML+endButtonRow);

				}

				$("#judgerecord_buttonarea").on(
					'click',
					'#print_judgerecord',
					function() {
						$("#judgerecord").trigger("printTable");
						return false;
					}
				);

				$("#judgerecord_buttonarea").on(
					'click',
					'#output_judgerecord',
					function() {

						$(".hiddencsv").addClass('yo');
						$(".hide_fromcsv").addClass('hiddencsv');
						$(".yo").removeClass('hiddencsv');

						$(".hidden_fromcsv .hiddencsv .yo").promise().done( function() {
							$("#judgerecord").trigger("outputTable");
						});

						$(".hide_fromcsv").removeClass('hiddencsv');
						$(".yo").addClass('hiddencsv');
						$(".hiddencsv").removeClass('yo');

						return false;
					}
				);


			$("#judgerecord_buttonarea").addClass("martop");

		});
